To use this program, simply enter CTYHDG. You will be given instructions.

This program will convert the files CQWW.CTY WAE.CTY and ARRL.CTY that are
shipped with K1EA's CT program, and will convert the file 0NA.CTY that is
shipped with K8CC's NA program, to include a little extra information in them.

If you use CT or NA, you probably already know the F10 key will tell you what
country a callsign belongs to.  This information comes from the .CTY files.
You may make your own beam heading support by altering these files.  For
example, you can change:

Spratly Island:           26:   1S:     1S;

to ...

Spratly Island (303):     26:   1S:     1S;

The result is that next time you enter a call starting with 1S and you hit
F10, you not only see Spratly Island on the screen, but also the beam heading.
The only problem is that the file is only good for your location, and it takes
a long time to update all the files.

This is where CTYHDG comes in.  This program contains will update your .CTY
files with the beam information from whatever latitude and longitude that you
like.  You will not reduce the available number of QSO's that are available to
you in either the CT or NA programs.  Not a bad feature for no loss of memory.

If a new country is assigned in the future, you may want to add the country
and prefix into both the CTYHDG.PRE file and the .CTY files.  In these files,
use the format shown.  In the CTYHDG.PRE file, do not go past column 26 for
the country description.  Also note that if a prefix shows up twice in this
file, only the first one is used.  The country description in this file is
only used if the original .CTY file contains a country description that goes
past column 21 (as of version 2.00 of CTYHDG), otherwise the country
description in the .CTY file is used. If you only update the .CTY file and not
the CTYHDG.PRE file, don't worry, the program will not destroy your .CTY file.
You will be informed of the prefix that was not found, and the original prefix
is transfered with no beam heading information.

